        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                Box 319.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44; Nov. 5 1882<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I feel very grate<lb/>ful for your kind lines of the 23d of last month<lb/> I would have answered before&#59; my little daug<lb/>ter Alice&#44; my first&#45;born&#44; has been seriously ill with<lb/> malarial fever and I had to give <hi rend="underline">her</hi> all the time<lb/> I could spare from my literary &#38; ministerial<lb/> labors.  I feel much better now than I did when<lb/> I wrote my last&#59; things do not look so gloomy&#44; per<lb/>haps&#44; because since then Mr Ch&#91;&#63;&#93; made a very<lb/> handsome &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Have you read the tribute<lb/> I paid his father&#44; the late Haham&#63;  He was a<lb/> good man&#44; a trifle weak and given to temporizing<lb/> <del>with</del> but he has succeeded in learning the repu<lb/>tation of a pious&#44; consistent man.  I liked the old<lb/> gentleman&#44; for he was very kind to the &#91;Hebrew&#93; in<lb/> Amsterdam and never stopped to think whether<lb/> they were Sephardim or <hi rend="underline">Judiscas</hi> as we are<lb/> called by the descendants of the exiles.  This ge<lb/>nerous consideration was considered a &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> in the old man&#44; and in consequence I felt&#44; when<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                Box 319.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;188<lb/></p>
            <p>he died&#44; I had a duty to perform &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> of course I <hi rend="underline">never</hi> thought of the son when I wrote<lb/> of the father &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; but Mr C. will have it&#44; that<lb/> I wrote the article &#34;knowing that it must touch<lb/> the tender cord of his filial affection&#34;¬ù and for<lb/> peace&#39; sake I am quite satisfied to let him have<lb/> his own stubborn way about it.  Your kind<lb/> advice&#44; I assure you&#44; has received due at<lb/>tention and deliberation&#44; and I would est<lb/>eem it an honor if you would occasionally<lb/> repeat it&#44; I fear&#44; that my old infirmity of tem<lb/>per has not yet forsaken me&#44; and though I<lb/> am indeed trying very hard to be kind and<lb/> gentle&#44; yet at times the hot blood drowns<lb/> all my honest intentions.  Well&#44; I am only<lb/> thirsty or will be next Sunday&#44; and whilst<lb/> I am praying&#44; that the next decade may be<lb/> the witness to my incessant labors for the house<lb/> of Israel&#44; I hope that with the hair&#44; that I am<lb/> losing very fast&#44; I may also lose my infirmities<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                Box 319.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;188<lb/></p>
            <p>of temper&#44; which have made me formerly more<lb/> enemies than I care to have.<lb/></p>
            <p>Regarding the &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; I have not received the vols.<lb/> mentioned.  I am quite content to send you the<lb/> amount in advance&#44; and will do so in a week<lb/> or two.  Just now I have not got it to spare.<lb/>  I will send you a p. o. order for &#36;3.50 which I<lb/> suppose will cover the amount.  If my coll&#44;<lb/>eagues have not yet reported please ad<lb/>vise me.  With many regards &#38; best wishes<lb/></p>
            <p>faithfully yours<lb/>
                Jacob Voorsanger<lb/></p>
                
            <p>B. I have taken charge of the <hi rend="underline">Sabbath Visitor</hi>.  Do<lb/> you get it&#63;  I should esteem it a favor&#44; if you could<lb/> find time to write a little something for the children.<lb/></p>
            <p><hi rend="underline">JV</hi><lb/></p>
        </body>
